    <title>Combined summary - Trusted merkle tree depth for safe tx inclusion proofs without a soft fork</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T03:16:48.389527+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2018-June/016091.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>A vulnerability has been discovered in the Bitcoin Merkle tree algorithm that could allow a miner to create a transaction falsely committed to a transaction not on the blockchain. RSK discovered this issue in 2017 and proposed two solutions: using version bits with 4 bits indicating the tree depth or banning transactions with a size of 64 or lower. The vulnerability can be avoided by comparing the length of the Merkle path to the known depth of the Merkle tree, which does not require a soft-fork to implement. Sergio Lerner reported a vulnerability affecting Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) wallets and other sensitive systems relying on SPV proofs. However, Peter Todd argues that pruned nodes can be made invulnerable to the attack while retaining the ability to verify merkle path tx inclusion proofs.Additionally, there is a low probability of SPV Wallet rejecting valid payments, but an attacker can fool it by creating a fake block at far less cost with a sybil attack. Bram Cohen proposes a soft fork to include the number of transactions in a block in the block headers to compensate for the broken Merkle format. However, Peter Todd notes that this vulnerability can be trivially avoided by simply comparing the length of the Merkle path to the known depth, which does not require a soft-fork to implement. Furthermore, the email conversation discusses an attack on SPV wallets and nodes that can bypass thousands of confirmations without a Sybil attack, affecting SPV wallets as well. However, the protections needed for SPV nodes to prevent such attacks are different and should be considered separately. One way for SPV nodes to avoid accepting payments is by checking if any Merkle node is at the same time a valid transaction, which essentially eliminates the problem.Peter Todd proposed a solution for the vulnerability by storing the depth of the Merkle tree in the block header database, allowing for safe verification of tx inclusion proofs without a soft-fork. Additionally, Todd discussed the Brute Force Cost Assuming a Valid Tx, suggesting that an attacker can have free choices of fields such as prevhash, prev_n, seq, nValue, pubk, and nLockTime, which can be fully brute-forcible or attainable with limited brute force. In an email conversation on June 9, 2018, Sergio Demian Lerner stated that an attacker having only $1.3 million could perform a brute-force attack on 72 bits in four days using ASICs and can thereby perform the same attack. However, Peter Todd noted that this did not make sense as one could fool a SPV wallet by creating a fake block at far less cost with a sybil attack.Finally, the concept of SPV is discredited and not worth concern. Despite this, the Bitcoin community must work to ensure the security and clean-design of Bitcoin.</summary>
